Here is a Java method that takes a comma-separated string as input and converts it to the desired format:

```
public class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        String input = "a, b, c";
        System.out.println(convertInput(input));
    }

    public static String convertInput(String input) {
        String[] values = input.split(", ");
        StringBuilder sb = new StringBuilder();
        for (int i = 0; i < values.length; i++) {
            sb.append(values[i]).append(" = '%s'");
            if (i < values.length - 1) {
                sb.append(" AND ");
            }
        }
        return sb.toString();
    }
}
```

In this code:

- The `convertInput` method takes a comma-separated string as input.
- It splits the input string into an array of values using the `split` method.
- It then iterates over the values array and appends each value to a `StringBuilder` in the desired format.
- If it's not the last value, it appends " AND " to separate the conditions.
- Finally, it returns the converted string.

You can test this method with different inputs, like "a, b, c", "x, y", or "foo, bar, baz", and it will produce the corresponding output.
